node.text:
Some facts about a whitetail fawn. They average 300 spots on their coat which they lose their spots around 4 months old when they grow their winter coats in October which have a grey tint to them. They are born with just 4 little teeth with no upper teeth and won’t get their “adult teeth” until 18 months of age or so. They nurse for months but they will start eating vegetation around 2-3 weeks old as well. New born fawns can stand and nurse just a few hours after birth but typically spend their first 2-3 weeks of life cuddled up in some thick brush and can usually outrun most danger just a couple weeks into their life. They are ready to mate by a year to year and a half old and will give birth 200 days after conception to a new 6-8 pound fawn and the cycle continues. The does that are 1.5 years old or younger will only give birth to one fawn but as they increase in age, twins are very very common.

node.text:
Y si el fin de semana tratamos de hacer una opción más saludable, hice la misma receta de Flammkuchen pero hoy como una pizza deliciosa.

Ingredientes para la masa
 •200g de harina de trigo integral (tiene un mayor aporte de fibra)
•2 cucharadas de aceite de oliva
•125 ml de agua
•1 cucharadita de sal
Ingredientes para los toppings 
•Queso mozzarella light
•Tomate (hice una salsa con tomates cherry y ajo)

Preparación
En un bowl se revuelven todos los ingredientes hasta formar una masa que no se pegue. (La harina, el agua, el aceite, sal y yo le puse orégano a la masa, lo revuelven con la mano hasta que tengan una masa que no se les pegue). Con un rodillo la aplanan, si no tienen, puede ser también con una botella de vino, hasta que quede una masa delgada. Después le agregan los ingredientes que quieran, yo le puse queso mozzarella, tomates, rugula y lo llevan al horno a 180grados por 10-15 minutos (esto va a depender de qué tab delgada les queda la masa y lo que le pongan por encima). Recuerda que para comer saludable debemos ser conscientes.

node.text: Hi !!! Your instagram is amazing ⭐, we’d like to collaborate with you, DM us 💫
Hi !!! Your instagram is amazing ⭐, we’d like to collaborate with you, DM us 💫

Got a spicy upper body workout for y’all today! 4 exercises, 10 repetitions each consecutively (all 4 exercises is one sequence) with a 30 second break in-between each sequence. Throwing in a little twist on today, I will be doing the workout all the way through so you can see the pacing and  follow along!

▫️My beginners and intermediates - your gonna aim for 3 rounds.  My advance people out there - you are going to aim for 4 rounds completed. Whole workout will take you 10 minutes or less regardless of difficulty level!

▫️All your going to need is a set of dumbbells (~10-15lbs) and a chair. We’re doing fair amount of volume in a very short period of time, so don’t go to crazy with the weight and focus on good technique. 

  The Exercises

1. Warmup 

2. Tricep Dips - focus on extending through the elbow not the hips 

3. King Kong Curls - keep your back locked in and straight!

4. Renegade Pushups - Lead with the chest not the shoulders (very important!)

5. Dumbbell Pronated Rows - think of your hands as hooks and pull through the elbow

Definitely save this workout, and give it shot. Lets finish the week strong and get those gains. 

Let’s get moving,
B

node.text:
FUN FACT ALERT!!!

Over 53 years after the discovery of Lynch syndrome, 95% of those who are positive for Lynch syndrome STILL do not know it. 

YOU or someone you LOVE could be one of these people!

This is why Mayberry Memorial exists.
 
It is frequently stated that it takes an average of 17 years for research evidence to reach clinical practice. Lynch syndrome was formerly known as Hereditary Nonpolyposis Colorectal Cancer. Currently, these two nomenclatures each have their unique definitions and are no longer used interchangeably. The history of hereditary nonpolyposis colorectal cancer was first recognized formally in the literature by Henry Lynch in 1967. 

Visit our link in our bio to support our mission!
